    <text xml:space="preserve">
      <body>
			<div type="edition">
				<ab>
					<lb n="1"/>
					<g ref="sym:san-siddham" type="ideogram">@</g>
					<g ref="sym:doubleBar" type="punctuation">.</g> tdaṃḥ ḅaṁḥ O hi tr̥ hna ku harivikrama ḅaṁḥ sniḥ ṅa
					<supplied reason="lost">s</supplied>u kni rla hniṁ tiṁ phvuṃ npu
					plaṁ ta kiṁ kha O sniḥ sniḥ plaṁ
					su taṁ rla kni tiṁ phvuṃ tko tiṁ tdaṃḥ ḅaṁḥ O ru kleḥ yaṁ <!-- MM2AG: should I do anything with the red in the RTF? -->
					<!-- AG2MM3: editing conventions to be revised. -->
				</ab>
			</div>
			<div type="apparatus">
				<listApp>
					<app loc="1">
						<lem>npu</lem>
						<note>If the meaning is ‘twenty four days’, then the akṣara should read nsu. Luce’s estampage might support &lt;n&gt;, but less so &lt;s&gt;. The urn has been damaged since Luce’s rubbing and that akṣara has been chipped off.</note>
						<!-- AG2MM3: just yesterday we revised our reading of 007-008, and decided one really cannot read nsu there, as we had in previous RTF. We now read rpu, but npu might also be possible; or this urn to be read rpu? -->
						<!-- MM2AG: should I wait unitl the 005 rtf is revised to add something about this change of mind? -->
					</app>
				<app loc="1">
						<lem>tr̥</lem>
						<rdg source="bib:Blagden1913-1914_01">t(r)a</rdg>
						<rdg source="bib:ThaMyat1963_01">tra</rdg>
					</app><app loc="1">
						<lem>ku</lem>
						<rdg source="bib:Blagden1913-1914_01">(ka)</rdg>
						<rdg source="bib:ThaMyat1963_01">(ka)</rdg>
					</app><app loc="1">
						<lem>ṅa</lem>
						<rdg source="bib:Blagden1913-1914_01">(ṅ)a</rdg>
						<rdg source="bib:ThaMyat1963_01">(ṅa)</rdg>
					</app><app loc="1">
						<lem><supplied reason="lost">s</supplied>u kni rla</lem>
						<rdg source="bib:Blagden1913-1914_01">sū kni (de)</rdg>
						<rdg source="bib:ThaMyat1963_01">sū kni (de)</rdg>
					</app><app loc="1">
						<lem>npu</lem>
						<rdg source="bib:Blagden1913-1914_01">(t)pū</rdg>
						<rdg source="bib:ThaMyat1963_01">nsū</rdg>
					</app><app loc="1">
						<lem>plaṁ</lem>
						<rdg source="bib:Blagden1913-1914_01">p(ḷ)aṁ</rdg>
					</app><app loc="1">
						<lem>kiṁ kha</lem>
						<rdg source="bib:Blagden1913-1914_01">(k)iṁ (kha)</rdg>
						<rdg source="bib:ThaMyat1963_01">kiṁ (kha)</rdg>
					</app><app loc="1">
						<lem>plaṁ</lem>
						<rdg source="bib:Blagden1913-1914_01">p(ḷ)aṁ</rdg>
					</app><app loc="1">
						<lem>su taṁ rla</lem>
						<rdg source="bib:Blagden1913-1914_01">sū taṁ (de)</rdg>
						<rdg source="bib:ThaMyat1963_01">sū taṁ (de)</rdg>
					</app><app loc="1">
						<lem>tko</lem>
						<rdg source="bib:Blagden1913-1914_01">t(k)o</rdg>
					</app><app loc="1">
						<lem>kleḥ</lem>
						<rdg source="bib:Blagden1913-1914_01">(kḷ)eḥ</rdg>
					</app></listApp>
			</div>
			<div type="translation" xml:lang="eng">
				<p>Blagden:</p>
				<ab>Year 57 (695 AD), 2nd month, 24th day; Harivikrama died; aged 41 years, 7 months and 9 days.</ab>
				<p>San Win:</p>
				<ab>On the 9th day of the 7th month in the (Pyu) year 41 King Hari Vikrama died. His age was 57 years, 2 months and 24 days.</ab>
			</div>
			<div type="commentary">
				<p>&lt;ru:&gt; cf. &lt;rūP&gt; in PYU <ref target="DHARMA_INSPYU00001">1</ref>.2?</p>
				<p>&lt;phvuṃ &gt;: note interesting allograph of &lt;-u&gt; associated with postconsonantal &lt;-v&gt;, more clearly detectable in PYU <ref target="DHARMA_INSPYU00006">6</ref>; also found in PYU 16.</p>
			</div>
			<div type="bibliography">
				<!--ASI 1911-12, 147. — ASB 1912, 7, 11. — Blagden 1913-14 (A). — PR, 47 (A), 50. — PPPB I, 48, 57 n. 13, 126-7.-->
				<!--[Todo: markup citedRange elements if necessary]-->
				<p><bibl><ptr target="bib:ASI"/><citedRange>1911-12:
					147</citedRange></bibl> reports the discovery of two urns with
					inscriptions, our PYU <ref target="DHARMA_INSPYU00005">5</ref> and <ref target="DHARMA_INSPYU00006">6</ref>, and cites Blagden, who viewed an estampage and noted the honorific &lt;tdaṃḥ ƀaṁḥ&gt;, relating it to the name of the legendary Duttabaung. <bibl><ptr target="bib:ASB"/><citedRange>1912: 7, 11</citedRange></bibl>, recapitulates much of the same information, but adds a reading of the name Harivikrama by the government epigraphist, Venkayya. <bibl><ptr target="bib:Blagden1913-1914_01"/><citedRange>(A)</citedRange></bibl> provides a complete reading, and a tentative translation. <bibl><ptr target="bib:ThaMyat1963_01"/><citedRange>47 (A), 50</citedRange></bibl>, provides eye copy, transliteration in Burmese script and English translation. <bibl><ptr target="bib:Luce1985_01"/><citedRange>I, 48, 57 n. 13, 126-7</citedRange></bibl>, constitutes an overview, and <bibl><ptr target="bib:SeinWin2016_01"/><citedRange>62</citedRange></bibl> provides another set of eye drawings and transliterations, with minor differences from earlier ones. Re-edited here from published photographs.</p>
			<listBibl type="primary"><bibl><ptr target="bib:CPI2018_01"/><citedRange unit="item">DHARMA_INSPYU00005</citedRange></bibl></listBibl></div>
		</body>
